 Canada today. And yet Indigenous religions continue to remain under threat. Framed through a postcolonial lens, What Has No Place, Remains analyses state actions, responses, and decisions on matters of Indigenous religious freedom. The book is particularly concerned with legal cases, such as Ktunaxa Nation v. British Columbia (2017), but also draws on political negotiations, such as those at Voisey’s Bay, and standoffs, such as the one at Gustafsen Lake, to generate a more comprehensive picture of the challenges for Indigenous religious freedom beyond Canada’s courts. With particular attention to cosmologically significant space, this book provides the first comprehensive assessment of the conceptual, cultural, political, social, and legal reasons why religious freedom for Indigenous Peoples is currently an impossibility in Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aFreedom of religionzCanada. 0aIndians of North AmericaxLegal status, laws, etczCanada. 0aIndians of North AmericaxLegal status, laws, etc.zCanada. 0aIndians of North AmericazCanadaxReligion. 7aLAW / Indigenous Peoples.2bisacsh  aCanada.  aCanada’s apology.  aGustafsen Lake.  aIndian Residential Schools.  aIndigenous Peoples.  aIndigenous.  aKtunaxa Nation v. British Columbia (2017).  aVoisey’s Bay.  aban.  acolonial.  apractices.  areligious freedom.  areligious.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065206240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148753073040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487530730423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487530730.jpg  a978-3-11-065206-2  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles